items.title: Coalition in freefall as Nationals quite shadow cabinet en masse
items.standfirst: Three Nationals senators who refused to join the Liberals in voting on the federal government's new hate speech and gun laws have quit the shadow cabinet.
items.content: The Coalition is in freefall after the fallout from a revolt in the Senate saw the entire Nationals' frontbench, including leader David Littleproud, quit. The move was triggered by division over the federal government's new hate speech laws, which forced three Nationals senators who refused to join the Liberals in voting for the reforms to hand in their resignations.Opposition Leader Sussan Ley confirmed in a statement today she had accepted the resignations of senators Susan McDonald, Bridget McKenzie and Ross Cadell. READ MORE: PM concedes hate speech and gun control laws are 'not as strong' as he hoped READ MORE: Emotional scenes as parliament honours Bondi terror victims But tonight, mass resignation went from a threat to reality as all eight remaining front bench Nationals quit after a momentous 24 hours in Canberra, sparking a crisis within the Coalition."Yesterday, in several conversations, I made it clear to David Littleproud that members of the shadow cabinet could not vote against the shadow cabinet position," Ley said earlier."The shadow cabinet was unanimous in its endorsement to support this bill subject to several amendments that we did then secure."This has been acknowledged by Nationals' senators this morning."Ley said McDonald, McKenzie and Cadell had been asked to continue to serve the Coalition but from outside of the shadow cabinet.She said Littleproud had been asked to put forward three replacement ministers. The new hate speech and gun laws were passed last night after a long night of voting in the Senate.The hate laws will create powers for authorities to designate certain organisations as "hate groups", allowing members and donors alike to face possible jail time.It will create new aggravated offences for religious or spiritual leaders who advocate violence, as well as penalise religious leaders who preach hate to children.The new framework will also give ministers more powers to cancel or refuse visas to those who spread hate or extremist views.The new gun laws, which were voted against by the Coalition, One Nation and United Australia Party senators but supported by the Greens, will limit the imports of guns to Australian citizens.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. Available on the Apple App Store and Google Play.
